</script>

Ever set padding to 13 pixels here, 17 there, 11 somewhere else? You've created a design crime scene. The fix? A spacing system where you pick from a small, fixed list. (CSI: UI Edition!)

Instead of any number from 1–100, you pick from a short, sacred list: 4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64.

Every margin and padding comes from this list. No sneaky decimals. No "it felt right." Consistent spacing creates rhythm your eye can dance to. Arbitrary spacing? That’s a conga line with everyone out of step.

The classic system uses multiples of 4:

```
4   → 1 unit   (barely there)
8   → 2 units  (small spacing)
12  → 3 units  (tight cards)
16  → 4 units  (standard padding)
24  → 6 units  (comfortable gaps)
32  → 8 units  (section spacing)
48  → 12 units (large section breaks)
64  → 16 units (page-level spacing)
```

Tailwind fans know these as p-1 through p-16.

## Rules

- Set your system before you build. No retrofitting.
- When two things need different spacing, move one step up or down, never jump randomly.
- Use system values everywhere: margins, padding, gaps.

